

namespace testing

README : Doc
README = {{
    # Testing

        Unison provides a means to test your code. As is often the case, there
        is extensive [documentation about testing](https://www.unison-lang.org/docs/usage-topics/testing/).
        Do make sure to look at that documentation as well.

    ## Benefits of Content Addressable Code

        Since Unison is build upon _content addressable code_ testing comes
        with an awesome feature: *caching*!

        So long definitions don't meaningfully change, there is no need to
        rerun tests.

        Your functions will have to be pure, i.e. do not have side-effects, but
        we will come to that later. For now just bask in the glory of not
        having to rerun tests when code doesn't change.

    ## Subject under Test

        It will be nice if we have a subject to test. For that we are going
        to use our humble {egcd}.

        @source{egcd}

        It doesn't really matter what it does, or how it does it. We are going
        to use it as a block box. You do have to trust me when I dictate the
        test cases though.

    ## Watch Expressions

        If you are lucky enough to have seen various demonstrations during the
        workshop, you might have seen _watch expression_ before. Those are
        little snippets of code that the ucm will evaluate, kind of like a
        Read-Eval-Print loop ( [REPL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Read%E2%80%93eval%E2%80%93print_loop) )

        ```plain
        > "Hello, " ++ "World!"
        ```

        will evaluate to

        ```
            "Hello, " ++ "World!"
        ```

        Testing relies on a special variant of a watch expression; a
        _test watch expression_. It is little more than a angle bracket (`>`)
        preceded by the word "test".

    ## Convention

        There is a convention for tests in Unison. The convention dictates that
        they are placed under the `tests` namespace under the term itself.

        Furthermore; the convention describes to number various tests like
        "ex1", "ex2" etcetera.

        It is just a convention and you are free to choose your own convention.

    ## First Test

        Let's write our first test

        @source{egcd.tests.ex1}

        Don't forget to make a test watch expression for it. If everything is
        done correctly you should see the ucm report something like:

        ```plain
            71 | test> egcd.tests.ex1 = test.verify do
    
            ✅ Passed Passed
        ```

        Once the code base is updated, you can ask to see the all test results
        with the `test` command

        ```plain
        > test
        ```


        It outputs a series of known tests:

        {{ Aside {{ Notice that is says that the test results are cached! }} }}

        ```plain
          Cached test results (`help testcache` to learn more)

            1. testing.egcd.tests.ex1   ◉ Passed

          ✅ 1 test(s) passing

          Tip: Use view 1 to view the source of a test.
        ```

    ## Delayed Computations

        {{ Aside {{
            Unlike [Haskell](https://www.haskell.org/) Unison isn't
            [_lazy evaluated_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lazy_evaluation)

            So Unison evaluates it's arguments. In order to delay that
            evaluation it is a common practice among non-lazy language, like
            Unison to wrap your argument in an abstraction, i.e. a wrap it 
            in a anonymous function.

            Since this happens often in Unison code there is syntac for it.
        }} }}

        When you view the {test.verify} function and look at it's signature,
        it might be a bewildering experience:

        @signature{test.verify}

        First, there is all the stuff between curly brackets `{}`! Those are
        abilities and we will get to them in the next section.

        Second there is the single quote `'`! What is that?

    ### Syntactic Sugar

        You can define anonymous function with the following syntax:

        ```
            n -> n + 37 
        ```

        But what if we don't need the argument? We can use ignore it with an
        underscore `_` saving our creativity when we really need to name
        something.

        ```
            _ -> 37 
        ```

        To call a function you have to provide an argument

        ```
            (n -> n + 37)(51)
        ```

        or in the function without an argument name

        ```
           (_ -> 37)() 
        ```


        {{ Aside {{
            I am about to tell a lie. For the function that produces a 37
            without inspecting its argument the _inferred_ type signature is

            @signature{README.actual_thirtyseven}

            But that would open up an other can of worms.
        }}}}

        The unison compiler would provide the following types, respectively

        @signature{README.add37}

        @signature{README.thirtyseven}

        There that interesting single quote `'Nat` again! But now we know it
        is just syntactic sugar for the `() -> Nat`, nothing more nothing less.

        It would also be cumbersome to keep on writing `_ -> block of code`.
        The syntactic sugar for that is `do`

        For example `do 37` is equivalent to

        ```
            do
                37
        ```
    
    ## Long Story Short

        `test.verify` accepts a _delayed computation_ that produces a
        {type List} of {type Result}.

    ## What _Abilities_ does {test.verify} provide us with

        Testing can be made more descriptive with:

    ### {type Label}

        Let's create variables for our test and label them:

        @source{egcd.tests.ex2}

        As is, nothing will chance. That is because the test passes. The real
        difference comes when a test fails. We will create a faulty test.

        @source{egcd.tests.faulty}

        then we get information about the labeled values.

        ```plain
            🚫 FAILED 
              egcd 37 51: 1
              x: 37
              y: 51
              elements not equal
              (1, 2)
        ```

        There is even a way to scope the {label}s with {labeled}

    ### Property Based Testing

        We can also test properties with {type Each} and {type Random}.

        @source{egcd.tests.ex3}

        Here {natIn} produces a {type Random} {type Nat} in a certain range.

    ## Exercises

        1. Write a test for your favorite function.
        2. What properties does your favorite function has.
}}


test> egcd.tests.ex3 = test.verify do
    Each.repeat 100
    max = 1000
    a = natIn 1 max
    b = natIn 1 max
    k = natIn 1 max

    label "a" a
    label "b" b
    label "k" k

    (g, _, _) = egcd a b

    (h, _, _) = egcd (k * a) (k * b)

    ensureEqual (k * g) h

---

test> egcd.tests.faulty = test.verify do
    x = 37
    y = 51

    label "x" x
    label "y" y

    (g, _, _) = egcd 37 51

    label ("egcd " ++ (Nat.toText x) ++ " " ++ (Nat.toText y)) g

    ensureEqual g 2

---

test> egcd.tests.ex2 = test.verify do
    x = 37
    y = 51

    label "x" x
    label "y" y

    (g, _, _) = egcd 37 51

    label ("egcd " ++ (Nat.toText x) ++ " " ++ (Nat.toText y)) g

    ensureEqual g 1


---

README.add37 n =
    n + 37

README.thirtyseven : () -> Nat
README.thirtyseven _ =
    37

README.actual_thirtyseven _ =
    51

---

> n -> n + 37
> (n -> n + 37)(51)
> _ -> 37
> (_ -> 37)()

---

test> egcd.tests.ex1 = test.verify do
    (g, _, _) = egcd 37 51

    ensureEqual g 1


---

> "Hello, " ++ "World!"
